'''Paul Eells''' ([[1935]] &ndash; [[July 31]] [[2006]]) was an [[United States|American]] [[sportscaster]]. He was the "Voice of the [[Arkansas Razorbacks|Razorbacks]]", broadcasting [[University of Arkansas]] [[college basketball|basketball]] games on television and (since 1978) [[college football|football]] games on radio.  Eells was also sports director at [[KATV]] television in [[Little Rock, Arkansas]].

[[Image:Eells.jpg|thumb|Paul Eells, Voice of the Arkansas Razorbacks]]

Eells was originally from [[Iowa]] but later moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] before living the rest of his life in central Arkansas. During his ten-year stay in Nashville, he was Sports Director at [[WSM-TV]] later [[WSMV-TV]] and Voice of the [[Vanderbilt Commodores]] on radio.  In 1978, he moved to central Arkansas to become sports director at KATV in Little Rock; radio play-by-play announcer for the Razorbacks football team, TV play-by-play announcer for the Razorbacks basketball team, and host of the TV football and basketball host of the Razorbacks coaches shows.   He was known statewide for his fantastic broadcasting voice and his trademark "Oh My" and "Touchdown Arkansas" radio calls.

Eells was inducted into the [[Arkansas Sports Hall of Fame]] in 2006.  He was also named Arkansas Sportscaster of the Year eleven times, and was also honored several times with an [[Associated Press]] award for best sports play-by-play.

Eells died in an [[auto accident]] on [[Interstate 40]] in [[Russellville, Arkansas]] at the age of 70. He lived in [[Maumelle, Arkansas]] at the time of his death.

